  "debug_data_path": "debug_data/2020_769",
  "eprint": {
    "title": "Lattice-Based Blind Signatures, Revisited",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Eduard Hauck",
        "email": "lossjulian@gmail",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Eike Kiltz",
        "email": "kiltz@rub",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Julian Loss",
        "email": "hauck@rub",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Ngoc Khanh Nguyen",
        "email": "deNKN@zurich",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "We observe that all previously known lattice-based blind signature schemes\ncontain subtle flaws in their security proofs (e.g., Rückert, ASIACRYPT '08) or can be attacked (e.g., BLAZE by Alkadri et al., FC '20).\nMotivated by this, we revisit the problem of constructing blind signatures from standard lattice assumptions.\n\nWe propose a new three-round lattice-based blind signature scheme whose security can be proved, in the random oracle model, from the standard SIS assumption. Our starting point is a modified version of the (insecure) BLAZE scheme, which itself is based Lyubashevsky's three-round identification scheme  combined with a new aborting technique to reduce the correctness error.\nOur proof builds upon and extends the recent modular framework for blind signatures of Hauck, Kiltz, and Loss\n(EUROCRYPT '19). It also introduces several new techniques to overcome the additional challenges posed by the correctness error which is inherent to all lattice-based constructions.\n\nWhile our construction is mostly of theoretical interest, we believe it to be an important stepping stone for future works in this area.",
    "keywords": [
      "Blind Signatures"
    ],
    "category": "Public-key cryptography",
    "publication_info": "A minor revision of an IACR publication in CRYPTO 2020",
    "last_updated": "2021-01-02",
    "license": "CC BY",
    "related_papers": []
  }
